25	2d/ae-for-cel	2db45da0d96b15f7e1d53d7fbb97af4c896d6169	AE for Cel: Setup + Best Practices		f	t	\N			<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h1 style="text-align:center;">AE for Cel: Setup + Best Practices</h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><a href="#h.v5scpsyh6yl1">Project Folder Structure</a></p>\n<p><a href="#h.pn056n6aiu5x">Project Setup</a></p>\n<p><a href="#h.vtwbjvekhsbc">Prepping and Optimizing the Artwork for Comp</a></p>\n<p><a href="#h.tfroe3tbxzcb">PSD File Prep Tips:</a></p>\n<p><a href="#h.8pem8yfwdkvw">Ai File Prep Tips:</a></p>\n<p><a href="#h.tc0bbajg7e3u">Cutdowns/Social Crops</a></p>\n<p><a href="#h.lppmxr4i5zjm">Workflow Best Practices + Watch Outs</a></p>\n<p><a href="#h.etlqgqi3rmzm">Protip for Naming Renders</a></p>\n<p><a href="#h.txphm24k145n">Exporting Layered PSDs from AE for Stills</a></p>\n<p><a href="#h.4efcv65nmha0">Handy Tools</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Project Folder Structure</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Overview</strong></p>\n<figure class="image"><img src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-_Oyg8a-bEXq1Q8Tt9Qqc6PVClCW0TLAzKlrbVfCq-MCRxxjNap21NYx6LcmKXglq49A47VX97XeHoQeqHtztIE9QZJxY_nJytA1a9WRJUaugpaamD7hNAfP6SC0Xkhq3A=w1280"></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>01_ae_project-files</p>\n<p>All project files should live here. Archive old projects and Logs directories in the archive folder.</p>\n<p>In here you will find a template file for comp. It contains timecode stamps which can be toggled on and off using a single control. All instructions are provided in a note layer in the comp. This also contains all 4 social crop sizes.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>02_ae_assets</p>\n<p>All assets you are linking to in your AEP should be in here. Copy over assets as the producer links things to you. Another artist should be able to sync only the AE directory and have all of your assets link up. If you need another folder, feel free to add it.</p>\n<p><strong><u>Notes</u></strong></p>\n<p><strong>04_footage</strong></p>\n<p>Any type of video file. This includes prerenders, stock, and animatics.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>05_Collected_Project_Files</strong></p>\n<p>Collected projects from other artists that you are bringing into your comp.</p>\n<p><u>Example:</u> You’re using end tags from a spot made last year. Collect the end tags here and import into your AEP.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>03_ae_output</p>\n<p>This is where your renders will go within a dated folder.* This directory is also for any reference videos/images you need to kick out of AE for 2D.</p>\n<p><i>*Once you QC your render, copy dailies for director review into dailies in the project root, and postings for client should go into post in the project root.*</i></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Project Setup</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Prepping and Optimizing the Artwork for Comp</strong></p>\n<p>Always keep the original approved art files intact. Do not modify those. Duplicate and save a new version when you make optimization edits.</p>\n<p>There is almost never an occasion where you should import approved designs directly into AE without doing some prep work first.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>PSD File Prep Tips:</p>\n<p>Reduce file size by merging and rescaling PSD art for AE.</p>\n<p>If you aren’t zooming in very tight or doing a long pan, there’s seldom a reason to use a PSD that is 6k+ resolution. Reduce PSD size to be 4K square (3840 x 3840). This can potentially reduce render times by HALF!</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Move and rename PSDs to appropriate ae assets folder:</p>\n<p>01_ae -&gt; 02_ae_assets -&gt; 02_psd-raster</p>\n<p>Prep files and move to psd or ai folders accordingly within ae assets.</p>\n<p>3. Rename files so they are consistent in shot naming.</p>\n<p>Oftentimes there are several designers working on one project and their naming conventions/shot numbers are not up to date. This can make tracking down specific PSDs difficult. Sample naming convention here.</p>\n<figure class="image"><img src="https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/fUDyjspZDAsMEo2IXstHyTB6WRTCt0sGpz2UFYzbHqKGxZKONi0DIz-kk3d0TTK0ntMulgeFnjVL_nZ9a8IfLIdFN5GWrmCgBmu8hIdOH2mb6ostbiAM1gXNwCyXrO6bGA=w1280"></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Ai File Prep Tips:</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Texture File</strong></p>\n<p>Designers should also provide you with a texture PSD along with any bespoke brushes they used for Ai or PS in case you need to make a very specific texture element for matting. If this has not been provided, please ask your Producer if that can be acquired.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Workflow</strong></p>\n<p>If the designer created the files in Ai and added textures in PS, you should recreate the look of the approved art in AE using the Ai layers (or shape layers if you have converted them) and the texture file you receive from the designers.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Use the Ai/shape layers as an alpha matte for your PS textures. This will give you the greatest flexibility to edit art on the fly. You can also create the textures using a bright red brush in PS, then add a “Fill” effect in AE to change the texture color as needed.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Mimic PS brush edges</strong></p>\n<p>If your art has a rough paper tooth texture edge and you’re using vector art, use the ROUGHEN EDGES plugin and adjust settings as needed. This can do the trick to simulate almost any PS brush you need to match the look of.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Cutdowns/Social Crops</strong></p>\n<p>Always build 9x16 as your hero social crop.</p>\n<p>If done correctly, 1x1 and 4x5s should be able to be cut from this video in Premiere.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>You can and should talk to 2D to ask for extended size animations.</p>\n<p>You may realize that in your vertical version the character isn’t tall enough to fill frame. Simply show 2D a reference image of your comp and they can extend their animation for you.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>End Cards</p>\n<p>When possible, build end cards to be the exact size of your exports.</p>\n<p>Example: You have a 1080x1920 export, your end card should be 1080x1920. We frequently need to swap end cards so this will save time down the line.</p>\n<figure class="table">\n  <table>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p><strong>Workflow Best Practices + Watch Outs</strong></p>\n          <p><strong>Use a One-Node Camera (don’t using multiple camera nulls)</strong></p>\n          <p>Under “Type” settings, select 1 node camera. This doesn’t use the “point of interest” and makes the camera function as if it was a standard 3d layer.</p>\n          <p>&nbsp;</p>\n          <p>If you want to look at something specific, simply adjust the rotation/position values of the camera.</p>\n          <p>&nbsp;</p>\n          <p>Making edits to this type of camera is significantly easier than a Two-Node cam.</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <figure class="image"><img src="/workflow.png"></figure>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n</figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong><u>Things to Avoid</u></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Extreme Z Space Values</strong></p>\n<p>Create Z depth ideally under 10,0000 px. Extreme depth can slow render times and make it difficult to locate layers in top view. If you need something to look deeper, try adjusting your camera settings. I.E. use a 200mm camera instead of 50mm.</p>\n<p><strong>DOF on Cameras</strong></p>\n<p>Slow. Very slow.</p>\n<p><strong>Motion Blur</strong></p>\n<p>You can use motion blur if needed, but it will slow your renders for sure. Perhaps try a directional gaussian blur on an adjustment layer to fake motion blur when you need it if it’s rendering slowly.</p>\n<p><strong>Large Particle Generators</strong></p>\n<p>They should not exceed 1080x1920 or 1920x1080. If you are using Particular, create a solid that is your comp size and apply the effect to that. Change your emitter width instead of widening the layer size. Your particles will still emit as though you had a much wider layer. This can save HOURS of rendering.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Protip for Naming Renders</strong></p>\n<p>You can create a custom output module so you don’t need to rename your renders every time. Once you get this set up, you can use it across any project - it even remembers it between AE updates.</p>\n<p>In your render queue, click that down arrow next to the Output To:</p>\n<figure class="image"><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/TX2bU_vVT2h5ETVw1iilM-QNat-q1U5SceSWfuhOW348VhTISO0mKX5AZJBnN9CR8maaDRPrToymuc0TzJybg8i7eM65-EbifhTox_spy-WPHDJSNyNvIDO_cI9kDgCoQg=w1280"></figure>\n<p>2. Select <strong>“Custom…” </strong>It will open up this dialogue:</p>\n<figure class="image"><img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/6mNkDCRANrNA_VD4ZQYrITdQhNSeydAEHQk31p9vWZj3Obw1MoS9VFYmuqM7jFUyKUkVpH7pciw3BGVDyF31p4yr_T4UY-yUT5DQILWXOeDTmrSYBT4PpH6H-7BwS8L15w=w1280"></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>3.<strong> COPY/PASTE THIS TEXT</strong> into your “Template:” text field:</p>\n<p><strong>[compName]_[dateYear][dateMonth][dateDay]_v01.[fileExtension]</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>4.<strong> Press the new preset button </strong>(looks like a layer button).</p>\n<p>5. Name your Preset IE: <strong>YearMonthDay_v01, </strong>click OK</p>\n<p>6. Then select “Default” back on the main menu. Every time you add a new file to your queue, it will automatically be given this naming convention.</p>\n<figure class="image"><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/TxsNK6M1PaSwubPmfx4sHe75IoQYZx8BCAhyqiWFqqnCATrX7oJ8-NSYlODST20rudd_6EFHAK-fE1se5QsQ0CwKNr1dJnj_k8io_7YibSXLwxDLCABgOpIZr9pIemamCQ=w1280"></figure>\n<figure class="image"><img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/n2F_eEMw1Q8aoroBK4F3ZLaxnAm-kMkyPvq8XpESuYUlQsvliJnEnap2a35szXF_Omz73blaf5uV5jvaDvVWZVpr1rjm3LKMJDvULBdAaiVL7CTXPykBnNHf55lsPDBRbQ=w1280"></figure>\n<p><i><strong>**Note: </strong>It’s not smart enough to know how to version up. To combat this, repeat the steps (except for changing your preset to “Default”), creating presets exactly. Like this for versions 2 through 4:</i></p>\n<figure class="image"><img src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/Uq2XM51RkNU3P83XfBlOKCJA3N0EPgU8EHSkWq3GzfZ0-e4-2DhV8xVVdzgADKFjFf5kdEIU9NMhlJM0pRvk1_M2GpVJfz99cxnkaOt6YvZch1qy3bqTI0LztVGyadV0zw=w1280"></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>7. If rendering through Media Encoder</strong>, add your render to your Render Queue, then press the “Queue in AME” button.</p>\n<p>If you do this, it will retain this naming convention. If you launch your render to ME directly from your AE comp, it will not use this naming convention.</p>\n<figure class="image"><img src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/olD8seQDCTjU3SYbZtZ_LhI0IzzBVsu2c0ejbHrKg81wJ5Y2-jFOoRUQcXzlqXkVKAfmsmnlyqCgi79f7XlRSqefOCku7Qq15gYnDmKtUZa-gUeOIzEDnDu6VtTmKHl7RA=w1280"></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Exporting Layered PSDs from AE for Stills</strong></p>\n<p>Sometimes clients ask for high res stills from our videos. If the art has been manipulated enough during comp, it will likely need to come from AE rather than from the original design files. On the frame you wish to save, navigate to the following menu.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><i>**<strong>Note:</strong> AE will render your layered still at the resolution in which you are previewing your comp. If your view is set to “Quarter” your PSD will be ¼ of the size of your 1920x1080 frame. Always set your preview to FULL before launching this.</i></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<figure class="image image_resized" style="width:100%;"><img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/DYHz_J2vYFusB6pJ4GFuz5pWbsing6AlkZqVTUYdjrCZM1zdU-1uxDeN8uqMEPTQjK8yov_VmHlGsdggq-rf6-SFwfkhCki3LlUY4xOMBhHWuPsqwW6JCmml0KbyWalWsA=w1280"></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Handy Tools</strong></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.battleaxe.co%2Foverlord&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNFXaiZM_X2K4QQfBEUQdfXnpHO2vw"><strong><u>Overlord</u></strong></a></p>\n<p>Pushes Ai type (great for end cards) and other vector art directly to AE (creates shape layers and live type) without needing to import Ai files.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Faescripts.com%2Fauto-crop%2F&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNEEaZJzEi7hwSUJDcWbDbaWntn7LQ"><strong><u>Autocrop</u></strong></a></p>\n<p>Have a precomp with a massive alpha channel? Crop it!</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Frainboxlab.org%2Ftools%2Fduik%2F&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNFFrThmn5J1dueoWR6GdM588UA76w"><strong><u>Duik</u></strong></a></p>\n<p>Duik comes with a whole host of tools that are handy for compositing. Notably:</p>\n<p>use the renaming function (allows you to quickly rename layers as well as project panel items).</p>\n<p>use the “scale z link” function to blow 3d layers out in space while maintaining proper scaling.</p>\n	<p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><h1 class="toc-header" id="ae-for-cel-setup-best-practices" style="text-align:center;"><a href="#ae-for-cel-setup-best-practices" class="toc-anchor">¶</a> AE for Cel: Setup + Best Practices</h1><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.v5scpsyh6yl1">Project Folder Structure</a></p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.pn056n6aiu5x">Project Setup</a></p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.vtwbjvekhsbc">Prepping and Optimizing the Artwork for Comp</a></p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.tfroe3tbxzcb">PSD File Prep Tips:</a></p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.8pem8yfwdkvw">Ai File Prep Tips:</a></p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.tc0bbajg7e3u">Cutdowns/Social Crops</a></p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.lppmxr4i5zjm">Workflow Best Practices + Watch Outs</a></p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.etlqgqi3rmzm">Protip for Naming Renders</a></p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.txphm24k145n">Exporting Layered PSDs from AE for Stills</a></p><div>\n</div><p><a href="#h.4efcv65nmha0">Handy Tools</a></p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>Project Folder Structure</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Overview</strong></p><div>\n</div><figure class="image"><img src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-_Oyg8a-bEXq1Q8Tt9Qqc6PVClCW0TLAzKlrbVfCq-MCRxxjNap21NYx6LcmKXglq49A47VX97XeHoQeqHtztIE9QZJxY_nJytA1a9WRJUaugpaamD7hNAfP6SC0Xkhq3A=w1280"></figure><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>01_ae_project-files</p><div>\n</div><p>All project files should live here. Archive old projects and Logs directories in the archive folder.</p><div>\n</div><p>In here you will find a template file for comp. It contains timecode stamps which can be toggled on and off using a single control. All instructions are provided in a note layer in the comp. This also contains all 4 social crop sizes.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>02_ae_assets</p><div>\n</div><p>All assets you are linking to in your AEP should be in here. Copy over assets as the producer links things to you. Another artist should be able to sync only the AE directory and have all of your assets link up. If you need another folder, feel free to add it.</p><div>\n</div><p><strong><u>Notes</u></strong></p><div>\n</div><p><strong>04_footage</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>Any type of video file. This includes prerenders, stock, and animatics.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>05_Collected_Project_Files</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>Collected projects from other artists that you are bringing into your comp.</p><div>\n</div><p><u>Example:</u> You’re using end tags from a spot made last year. Collect the end tags here and import into your AEP.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>03_ae_output</p><div>\n</div><p>This is where your renders will go within a dated folder.* This directory is also for any reference videos/images you need to kick out of AE for 2D.</p><div>\n</div><p><i>*Once you QC your render, copy dailies for director review into dailies in the project root, and postings for client should go into post in the project root.*</i></p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>Project Setup</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Prepping and Optimizing the Artwork for Comp</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>Always keep the original approved art files intact. Do not modify those. Duplicate and save a new version when you make optimization edits.</p><div>\n</div><p>There is almost never an occasion where you should import approved designs directly into AE without doing some prep work first.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>PSD File Prep Tips:</p><div>\n</div><p>Reduce file size by merging and rescaling PSD art for AE.</p><div>\n</div><p>If you aren’t zooming in very tight or doing a long pan, there’s seldom a reason to use a PSD that is 6k+ resolution. Reduce PSD size to be 4K square (3840 x 3840). This can potentially reduce render times by HALF!</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>Move and rename PSDs to appropriate ae assets folder:</p><div>\n</div><p>01_ae -&gt; 02_ae_assets -&gt; 02_psd-raster</p><div>\n</div><p>Prep files and move to psd or ai folders accordingly within ae assets.</p><div>\n</div><p>3. Rename files so they are consistent in shot naming.</p><div>\n</div><p>Oftentimes there are several designers working on one project and their naming conventions/shot numbers are not up to date. This can make tracking down specific PSDs difficult. Sample naming convention here.</p><div>\n</div><figure class="image"><img src="https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/fUDyjspZDAsMEo2IXstHyTB6WRTCt0sGpz2UFYzbHqKGxZKONi0DIz-kk3d0TTK0ntMulgeFnjVL_nZ9a8IfLIdFN5GWrmCgBmu8hIdOH2mb6ostbiAM1gXNwCyXrO6bGA=w1280"></figure><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>Ai File Prep Tips:</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Texture File</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>Designers should also provide you with a texture PSD along with any bespoke brushes they used for Ai or PS in case you need to make a very specific texture element for matting. If this has not been provided, please ask your Producer if that can be acquired.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Workflow</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>If the designer created the files in Ai and added textures in PS, you should recreate the look of the approved art in AE using the Ai layers (or shape layers if you have converted them) and the texture file you receive from the designers.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>Use the Ai/shape layers as an alpha matte for your PS textures. This will give you the greatest flexibility to edit art on the fly. You can also create the textures using a bright red brush in PS, then add a “Fill” effect in AE to change the texture color as needed.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Mimic PS brush edges</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>If your art has a rough paper tooth texture edge and you’re using vector art, use the ROUGHEN EDGES plugin and adjust settings as needed. This can do the trick to simulate almost any PS brush you need to match the look of.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Cutdowns/Social Crops</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>Always build 9x16 as your hero social crop.</p><div>\n</div><p>If done correctly, 1x1 and 4x5s should be able to be cut from this video in Premiere.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>You can and should talk to 2D to ask for extended size animations.</p><div>\n</div><p>You may realize that in your vertical version the character isn’t tall enough to fill frame. Simply show 2D a reference image of your comp and they can extend their animation for you.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>End Cards</p><div>\n</div><p>When possible, build end cards to be the exact size of your exports.</p><div>\n</div><p>Example: You have a 1080x1920 export, your end card should be 1080x1920. We frequently need to swap end cards so this will save time down the line.</p><div>\n</div><figure class="table">\n  <table>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p><strong>Workflow Best Practices + Watch Outs</strong></p>\n          <p><strong>Use a One-Node Camera (don’t using multiple camera nulls)</strong></p>\n          <p>Under “Type” settings, select 1 node camera. This doesn’t use the “point of interest” and makes the camera function as if it was a standard 3d layer.</p>\n          <p>&nbsp;</p>\n          <p>If you want to look at something specific, simply adjust the rotation/position values of the camera.</p>\n          <p>&nbsp;</p>\n          <p>Making edits to this type of camera is significantly easier than a Two-Node cam.</p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <figure class="image"><img src="/workflow.png"></figure>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n</figure><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong><u>Things to Avoid</u></strong></p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Extreme Z Space Values</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>Create Z depth ideally under 10,0000 px. Extreme depth can slow render times and make it difficult to locate layers in top view. If you need something to look deeper, try adjusting your camera settings. I.E. use a 200mm camera instead of 50mm.</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>DOF on Cameras</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>Slow. Very slow.</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Motion Blur</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>You can use motion blur if needed, but it will slow your renders for sure. Perhaps try a directional gaussian blur on an adjustment layer to fake motion blur when you need it if it’s rendering slowly.</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Large Particle Generators</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>They should not exceed 1080x1920 or 1920x1080. If you are using Particular, create a solid that is your comp size and apply the effect to that. Change your emitter width instead of widening the layer size. Your particles will still emit as though you had a much wider layer. This can save HOURS of rendering.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Protip for Naming Renders</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>You can create a custom output module so you don’t need to rename your renders every time. Once you get this set up, you can use it across any project - it even remembers it between AE updates.</p><div>\n</div><p>In your render queue, click that down arrow next to the Output To:</p><div>\n</div><figure class="image"><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/TX2bU_vVT2h5ETVw1iilM-QNat-q1U5SceSWfuhOW348VhTISO0mKX5AZJBnN9CR8maaDRPrToymuc0TzJybg8i7eM65-EbifhTox_spy-WPHDJSNyNvIDO_cI9kDgCoQg=w1280"></figure><div>\n</div><p>2. Select <strong>“Custom…” </strong>It will open up this dialogue:</p><div>\n</div><figure class="image"><img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/6mNkDCRANrNA_VD4ZQYrITdQhNSeydAEHQk31p9vWZj3Obw1MoS9VFYmuqM7jFUyKUkVpH7pciw3BGVDyF31p4yr_T4UY-yUT5DQILWXOeDTmrSYBT4PpH6H-7BwS8L15w=w1280"></figure><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>3.<strong> COPY/PASTE THIS TEXT</strong> into your “Template:” text field:</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>[compName]_[dateYear][dateMonth][dateDay]_v01.[fileExtension]</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>4.<strong> Press the new preset button </strong>(looks like a layer button).</p><div>\n</div><p>5. Name your Preset IE: <strong>YearMonthDay_v01, </strong>click OK</p><div>\n</div><p>6. Then select “Default” back on the main menu. Every time you add a new file to your queue, it will automatically be given this naming convention.</p><div>\n</div><figure class="image"><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/TxsNK6M1PaSwubPmfx4sHe75IoQYZx8BCAhyqiWFqqnCATrX7oJ8-NSYlODST20rudd_6EFHAK-fE1se5QsQ0CwKNr1dJnj_k8io_7YibSXLwxDLCABgOpIZr9pIemamCQ=w1280"></figure><div>\n</div><figure class="image"><img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/n2F_eEMw1Q8aoroBK4F3ZLaxnAm-kMkyPvq8XpESuYUlQsvliJnEnap2a35szXF_Omz73blaf5uV5jvaDvVWZVpr1rjm3LKMJDvULBdAaiVL7CTXPykBnNHf55lsPDBRbQ=w1280"></figure><div>\n</div><p><i><strong>**Note: </strong>It’s not smart enough to know how to version up. To combat this, repeat the steps (except for changing your preset to “Default”), creating presets exactly. Like this for versions 2 through 4:</i></p><div>\n</div><figure class="image"><img src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/Uq2XM51RkNU3P83XfBlOKCJA3N0EPgU8EHSkWq3GzfZ0-e4-2DhV8xVVdzgADKFjFf5kdEIU9NMhlJM0pRvk1_M2GpVJfz99cxnkaOt6YvZch1qy3bqTI0LztVGyadV0zw=w1280"></figure><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>7. If rendering through Media Encoder</strong>, add your render to your Render Queue, then press the “Queue in AME” button.</p><div>\n</div><p>If you do this, it will retain this naming convention. If you launch your render to ME directly from your AE comp, it will not use this naming convention.</p><div>\n</div><figure class="image"><img src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/olD8seQDCTjU3SYbZtZ_LhI0IzzBVsu2c0ejbHrKg81wJ5Y2-jFOoRUQcXzlqXkVKAfmsmnlyqCgi79f7XlRSqefOCku7Qq15gYnDmKtUZa-gUeOIzEDnDu6VtTmKHl7RA=w1280"></figure><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Exporting Layered PSDs from AE for Stills</strong></p><div>\n</div><p>Sometimes clients ask for high res stills from our videos. If the art has been manipulated enough during comp, it will likely need to come from AE rather than from the original design files. On the frame you wish to save, navigate to the following menu.</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><i>**<strong>Note:</strong> AE will render your layered still at the resolution in which you are previewing your comp. If your view is set to “Quarter” your PSD will be ¼ of the size of your 1920x1080 frame. Always set your preview to FULL before launching this.</i></p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><figure style="width:100%;" class="image image_resized"><img src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/DYHz_J2vYFusB6pJ4GFuz5pWbsing6AlkZqVTUYdjrCZM1zdU-1uxDeN8uqMEPTQjK8yov_VmHlGsdggq-rf6-SFwfkhCki3LlUY4xOMBhHWuPsqwW6JCmml0KbyWalWsA=w1280"></figure><div>\n</div><p>&nbsp;</p><div>\n</div><p><strong>Handy Tools</strong></p><div>\n</div><p><a class="is-external-link" href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.battleaxe.co%2Foverlord&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNFXaiZM_X2K4QQfBEUQdfXnpHO2vw"><strong><u>Overlord</u></strong></a></p><div>\n</div><p>Pushes Ai type (great for end cards) and other vector art directly to AE (creates shape layers and live type) without needing to import Ai files.</p><div>\n</div><p><a class="is-external-link" href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Faescripts.com%2Fauto-crop%2F&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNEEaZJzEi7hwSUJDcWbDbaWntn7LQ"><strong><u>Autocrop</u></strong></a></p><div>\n</div><p>Have a precomp with a massive alpha channel? Crop it!</p><div>\n</div><p><a class="is-external-link" href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Frainboxlab.org%2Ftools%2Fduik%2F&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNFFrThmn5J1dueoWR6GdM588UA76w"><strong><u>Duik</u></strong></a></p><div>\n</div><p>Duik comes with a whole host of tools that are handy for compositing. Notably:</p><div>\n</div><p>use the renaming function (allows you to quickly rename layers as well as project panel items).</p><div>\n</div><p>use the “scale z link” function to blow 3d layers out in space while maintaining proper scaling.</p><div>\n</div>	[{"title":"AE for Cel: Setup + Best Practices","anchor":"#ae-for-cel-setup-best-practices","children":[]}]	html	2021-07-14T18:55:21.405Z	2021-07-14T18:58:52.236Z	ckeditor	en	1	3	{"js":"","css":""}
